{"questionId":"9071264","questionHtml":"<p>What is ΔH, in kJ, for the reaction N<sub>2</sub>H<sub>4</sub> (l) + H<sub>2</sub> (g) → 2NH<sub>3</sub> (g)?&nbsp;</p>\n<table style=\"height:136px;width:482.19px;\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"5\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:373px;text-align:center;\"><strong>Reaction</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width:62.1901px;text-align:center;\"><strong>ΔH</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:373px;text-align:left;\">N<sub>2</sub>H<sub>4</sub> (l) + CH<sub>3</sub>OH (l) → CH<sub>2</sub>O (g) + N<sub>2</sub> (g) + 3H<sub>2</sub> (g)</td>\n<td style=\"width:62.1901px;text-align:center;\">−37 kJ</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:373px;text-align:left;\">N<sub>2</sub> (g) + 3H<sub>2</sub> (g) → 2NH<sub>3</sub> (g)</td>\n<td style=\"width:62.1901px;text-align:center;\">−46 kJ</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:373px;text-align:left;\">CH<sub>3</sub>OH (l) → CH<sub>2</sub>O (g) + H<sub>2</sub> (g)</td>\n<td style=\"width:62.1901px;text-align:center;\">−65 kJ</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><br>A.&nbsp; −18</p>\n<p>B.&nbsp; 18</p>\n<p>C.&nbsp; −83</p>\n<p>D.&nbsp; −148</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>A</p>","meta":{"questionId":"9071264","referenceCode":"23M.1.SL.TZ2.14","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"What is ΔH, in kJ, for the reaction N2H4 (l) + H2 (g) → 2NH3 (g)? Reaction ΔH N2H4 (l) + CH3OH (l) → CH2O (g) + N2 (g) + 3H2 (g) −37 kJ N2 (g) + 3H2 (g) → 2NH3 (g) −46 kJ CH3OH (l)","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"14","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Additional higher level (AHL)","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 15: Energetics/thermochemistry","15.1 Energy cycles","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 15: Energetics/thermochemistry"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}